snippet.textDisplay:
Several questions come to mind on the launches. Your awd ratio being one of them. What's your ration between your front and rear. Being say 30 front 70 rear? A lot of cars being say like Subaru has factors put in for if traction has slipped or even your wheel hop. It one throws the traction somewhere else to pull you out of the hole. In doing so, if may limit the throttle. You can signal a 96% throttle but you may only get 54% for it doesn't want you making the "hole" worse. Also, if your ratio is close enough, shouldn't your suspension setup be more like an old gasser? Slight squish in the rear and stiffer in the front to plant it. What I'm getting at is, the AWD system should do some of the work of pulling you out of the hole faster. Again, another reference to Subaru and their launches. If you notice most of theirs they bounce like a rabbit cause of the 50/50 kind of ratio. Yet, a GTR kind of squats in the rear and rolls out. As for the wheel hop in the rear. Look up the fix for the 99-04 mustang wheel hop. That gen had terrible wheel hop. I can't remember but I believe it had something to do with a simple strut replacement or it was a strut flipped fixed it.

Be safe Jeremy, you'll figure it out soon.

snippet.textDisplay: Hey guys @Fasterproms I think you should try setting up the alignment in the front like a front wheel drive car, Brent over at PFI has explained a couple of times what his process is for tuning toe in. I think a little more toe in on the front would help lock the truck into a course, rather than fighting it at down the track. (Basically, start from the factory toe setting in the front and every pass add a turn of toe in to each side, you'll see the 60ft come down progressively and eventually get to a point where it reverses and starts loosing time. You then back the toe out a turn and are set) You want those front tires trying to drive toward themselves. You may have to do something different for road course work, but at the drag strip that should really help you out. I think the sketchyness at the top end is from too little toe in (or none at all).
snippet.textOriginal: Hey guys @Fasterproms I think you should try setting up the alignment in the front like a front wheel drive car, Brent over at PFI has explained a couple of times what his process is for tuning toe in.
